A simple way to wrap your head around ​root causes is with the process called the Five Whys. ​In the Five Whys you ask ​"why" five times to reveal the root cause.

Understanding Analytical Thinking and Root Cause Analysis with the Five Whys
  Analytical thinking is like having a toolbox filled with different ways to solve problems. It includes skills like visualizing information, making strategies, focusing on problems, seeing connections, and balancing big-picture and detailed thinking. Imagine you're trying to solve a puzzle: sometimes you look at the whole picture, and other times you focus on one piece. Being good at all these ways of thinking helps you find smart solutions, especially when answers aren't obvious.

One powerful tool in analytical thinking is the "Five Whys" technique, which helps find the root cause of a problem by asking "why" five times. For example, if you can't make a blueberry pie because there are no blueberries, you ask why. The answer might be that birds ate the berries because their usual food, mulberries, didn't grow due to a late frost. By digging deeper with each "why," you discover the real reason behind the problem, not just the surface issue. This method helps prevent problems from happening again by fixing the true cause.

Example: Improving Delivery Timeliness in Operations Management
  Problem: Your company is experiencing frequent delays in delivering products to customers.
    Why 1: Why are deliveries delayed? Because the delivery trucks often leave the warehouse late.
    Why 2: Why do trucks leave late? Because the loading process takes longer than scheduled.
    Why 3: Why does loading take longer? Because the warehouse staff have to search for items due to poor inventory organization.
    Why 4: Why is the inventory poorly organized? Because there is no standardized system for item placement and tracking.
    Why 5: Why is there no standardized system? Because the company has not implemented an inventory management software or clear procedures.

Root Cause: Lack of an effective inventory management system leads to delays in loading, causing late deliveries.

Relevance and Connection:
  This example shows how the Five Whys technique helps uncover the root cause behind a common operational problem.
  As an operations manager interested in data analysis, you can see how asking the right questions leads to identifying actionable solutions, such as implementing inventory management software.
  It connects the concept of analytical thinking with real-world business challenges, emphasizing problem-orientation and strategy.
